@dytiaaurinh I'm okay now huhuhu but just now after the appointment I just wanted to scream omg that was a clusterfuck. I wish I could say something to him as a rebuttal but tbh I didn't have the spoons to do so

Man I can't wait to tell my psychotherapist all about this. I'm so glad my psychotherapist is actually a sex positive, queer affirming mental health professional. Those who would like to engage in her service hmu I'll give you her contacts

So now we know my psychiatrist holds some disturbing views on sexuality. I mean I didn't expect much from a Malay Muslim male dr working in a govt hosp (sorry to say la) but he has never been like this before, for god's sake he even used to touch me in a suspicious manner

In the end, he told me "get married and you will find out if it's the right thing for you. If it works, then alhamdulillah, if not, Islam allows divorce" gila kau does he even realise how difficult it is for a Muslim woman to get a divorce here???

My godddd I can't imagine what kind of response he would give to LGBTQ folks, like, would he tell them to "just get married so that you can control your urges and be normal ikut fitrah like how God wanted you to be"??? Can you imagine how devastating that would be???

So in one single appointment, he managed to tell me 
1. As a woman, being poly is equal to being gay and that I need to "control those urges"
2. However, it's perfectly fine for men to be poly because "God made us like this"

He didn't just stop there!!! He then said "unlike men, by nature we are created to be polygamous, and that's why in Islam we have, em, provisions". By that time I was too stunned to say anything and I legit almost dissociated lmaooooo

He then went on to say "God created women to be monogamous, but in psychology we know that 20-30% of women are polyam. What matters is how you control those thoughts, and Islam has a solution to it"
In my heart I was like NO YOU DID NOT JUST SAY THAT LMAOOO

Mind you this is coming from a guy who ACTUALLY HAS TWO WIVES!
HE HIMSELF IS POLYGAMOUS!

He said "it's not sinful to have thoughts (coz I told him despite being poly I'm currently in a monogamous relationship of 6 years), but what matters is how you control your nafsu AND MARRIAGE WILL HELP YOU WITH THAT"
AHAHAHAHA

I didn't know what I expected from him though, but definitely not religious based advice because that has never happened before. Unfortunately he went on to give me what was essentially a tazkirah on kawal nafsu and kembali ke jalan benar

So aku dok cerita la macam2 and one of them was about marriage and my reluctance to proceed with it. I also told him I'm polyam (which explains the reluctance), to which he surprisingly responded "yes we're aware of that"

I half expected to see some random MO and get my Rx and next appointment and then blah, tapi hari ni just my luck that my psychiatrist was around so I got to meet him. And I got to talk to him about stuff I can't tell other MOs

Take home message?
Dealing with parents is a complex situation. 
I wouldn't want my hypothetical kid to feel what I feel, I don't want to end up regretting my decision to have kids and damaging their own mental health. Kids are clever, they pick up on these things.

I would like to thank my therapist for allowing me to not chastise myself for feeling this way lolz. Old society-conditioned, religious me would blame myself for FEELING SAD and label myself "tak bersyukur, anak tak kenang budi". Baru feel ok bukan abandon mak bapak aku pun

However, I think I still have the right to feel sad about the derailment of my own plans and ambitions. It's not too late to achieve them of course, but grief is complex and I think what I feel is a perfectly normal response that should not be seen as my being ungrateful

I don't resent my parents. They didn't plan to have a financial crisis to the point where they ended up struggling for 20 whole years living in hardship while bringing up all 3 of us. They sacrificed their own ambitions. It's only fair that they are rewarded for their sacrifices
I have to make peace with this. Pray that I will eventually.

I can argue that these plans are relatively selfish and do not take into account the very real possibilities of my parents having illnesses, like most ageing parents eventually will, and illnesses are costly - money and time wise
